diff --git a/doc/filters.texi b/doc/filters.texi
index 0b0663cd9d..e0a58ec7e9 100644
--- a/doc/filters.texi
+++ b/doc/filters.texi
@@ -13690,6 +13690,129 @@ fftfilt=dc_Y=0:weight_Y='exp(-4 * ((Y+X)/(W+H)))'
 
 @end itemize
 
+@anchor{fcvvdp}
+@section fcvvdp
+
+Calculate the fcvvdp (Fast Color Video Visual Difference Predictor)
+between two input videos.
+
+This filter takes in input two input videos, the first input is
+considered the "main" source and is passed unchanged to the
+output. The second input is used as a "reference" video for computing
+the fcvvdp score.
+
+Both video inputs must have the same resolution and pixel format for
+this filter to work correctly. Also it assumes that both inputs
+have the same number of frames, which are compared one by one.
+
+The fcvvdp filter currently supports RGB pixel formats.
+
+The filter computes a perceptual quality score over the entire video
+sequence using temporal pooling. The final CVVDP score is printed
+through the logging system after all frames are processed.
+
+The filter outputs two metrics:
+
+@table @option
+@item JOD (Just-Objectionable-Difference)
+A perceptual quality score ranging from 0 to 10, where higher values
+indicate better quality. A JOD score of 0 means the distorted image
+is indistinguishable from the reference.
+
+@item Quality score
+An internal quality metric before the JOD transform.
+@end table
+
+The description of the accepted parameters follows.
+
+@table @option
+@item stats_file, f
+If specified the filter will use the named file to save the fcvvdp score
+of each individual frame. When filename equals "-" the data is sent to
+standard output.
+
+@item display_model
+Set the CVVDP display model to use for the quality computation.
+It accepts the following values:
+
+@table @samp
+@item standard_fhd
+24" FullHD, 200 nit, office lighting (default)
+
+@item standard_4k
+30" 4K, 200 nit, office lighting
+
+@item standard_hdr_pq
+30" 4K HDR, 1500 nit, low light with PQ transfer function
+
+@item standard_hdr_hlg
+30" 4K HDR, 1500 nit, low light with HLG transfer function
+
+@item standard_hdr_linear
+30" 4K HDR linear color space
+
+@item standard_hdr_dark
+30" 4K HDR dark room
+
+@item standard_hdr_linear_zoom
+30" 4K HDR linear (close viewing)
+@end table
+
+@item threads
+Set the number of worker threads for fcvvdp computation. Default value
+is 0, which uses the filter's default number of threads.
+@end table
+
+This filter also supports the @ref{framesync} options.
+
+The file printed if @var{stats_file} is selected, contains per-frame
+intermediate results in key/value pairs of the form @var{key}:@var{value}
+for each compared couple of frames. Note that these are intermediate
+accumulated scores as CVVDP uses temporal pooling.
+
+A description of each shown per-frame-pair parameter follows:
+
+@table @option
+@item n
+sequential number of the input frame, starting from 1
+
+@item jod
+The accumulated JOD (Just-Objectionable-Difference) score.
+
+@item quality
+The accumulated quality score.
+@end table
+
+Note: Due to temporal pooling, the scores at each frame represent the
+accumulated quality up to that point. The final score reported at the
+end of processing is the CVVDP score for the entire sequence.
+
+@subsection Examples
+@itemize
+@item
+For example:
+@example
+movie=ref_movie.mpg, setpts=PTS-STARTPTS [main];
+[main][ref] fcvvdp="stats_file=stats.log" [out]
+@end example
+
+On this example the input file being processed is compared with the
+reference file @file{ref_movie.mpg}. The fcvvdp score of each individual
+frame is stored in @file{stats.log}.
+
+@item
+Another example with different containers:
+@example
+ffmpeg -i main.mpg -i ref.mkv -lavfi "[0:v]settb=AVTB,setpts=PTS-STARTPTS[main];[1:v]settb=AVTB,setpts=PTS-STARTPTS[ref];[main][ref]fcvvdp" -f null -
+@end example
+
+@item
+Use HDR PQ display model:
+@example
+ffmpeg -i distorted.mp4 -i reference.mp4 -lavfi "fcvvdp=display_model=standard_hdr_pq" -f null -
+@end example
+@end itemize
+
 @section field
 
 Extract a single field from an interlaced image using stride
